[{"id":"VR001894","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram of a ray of light in two materials. The diagram consists of a rectangle, which represents an Unknown Material, and a dashed line through the center of the rectangle, perpendicular to the top side of the rectangle. The area above the Unknown Material is labeled Air. The incident ray starts near the top of the figure, to the left of the dashed line. It moves downward and to the left. The angle of the ray with the dashed line is labeled theta sub x. The other ray extends out from the point where the first ray, the dashed line, and the top side of the rectangle meet. This ray moves downward and to the right. The angle of this ray with the normal is labeled theta sub Y, and the angle of this ray with the top of the rectangle is labeled theta sub Z.\" height=\"261\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR001894.g01.png\" width=\"450\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The figure illustrates an experiment to determine the index of refraction of an unknown material. A laser beam in air is incident on a block of the unknown material, and the angles <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub x\"><math alttext=\"theta sub x\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub y\"><math alttext=\"theta sub y\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub z\"><math alttext=\"theta sub z\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> can be measured. Which of the angles are needed to determine the index of refraction of the unknown material, and why are these angles needed?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR001894_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub x\"><math alttext=\"theta sub x\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub y\"><math alttext=\"theta sub y\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because these are the angle of incidence and angle of refraction, respectively.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub x\"><math alttext=\"theta sub x\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub z\"><math alttext=\"theta sub z\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because these are the angle of incidence and angle of refraction, respectively.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub y\"><math alttext=\"theta sub y\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub z\"><math alttext=\"theta sub z\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because both these angles are in the block.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub x\"><math alttext=\"theta sub x\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub y\"><math alttext=\"theta sub y\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub z\"><math alttext=\"theta sub z\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because all three angles are used in the equation relating the indices of refraction of the air and the unknown material.</p>"],"answer":0}]